Parasitic protozoa are known to reveal sialoglycoconjugates which play an important role in their biological function (Table 3
) and T. cruzi (Fig. 9
), the causative agent of life-threatening Chagas disease in South America, is known to express sialic acids transferred from the host glycoconjugates to the terminal β-galactopyranosyl residues of mucin-like molecules on parasite surface by using the enzyme trans-sialidase [180]. These sialic acids might play a role in conferring protection from the recognition and response by the host immune system. Sialic acid such as Neu5Ac, Neu5Gc, Neu5,7Ac2, and Neu5,9Ac2 have been reported to occur in Dictyostelium discoideum, a trypanosome Crithidia fasciculata (C. fasciculata), piroplasmid Theileria sergenti (T. sergenti), and amoebae Entamoeba invadens (E. invadens) and Entameoba histolytica (E. histolytica) [6], [181], [182], [183], [184], [185].
